1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,600
For loops are a versatile and powerful tool in Python,

2

00:00:03,600  -->  00:00:05,480
especially when you know the number of

3

00:00:05,480  -->  00:00:08,920
iterations or times you need to run your code in advance.

4

00:00:08,920  -->  00:00:12,740
A for loop is used for iterating over a sequence of items,

5

00:00:12,740  -->  00:00:14,840
as in a list of things.

6

00:00:14,840  -->  00:00:17,460
Such groups of things can be called the list,

7

00:00:17,460  -->  00:00:20,800
tuple, dictionary, set, or string.

8

00:00:20,800  -->  00:00:23,200
Don't worry if you don't recognize these words.

9

00:00:23,200  -->  00:00:26,060
They are going to be explained later in the course.

10

00:00:26,060  -->  00:00:31,760
All you have to know is that loops allow you to execute a block of code for each item in

11

00:00:31,760  -->  00:00:35,040
the sequence and are particularly useful when

12

00:00:35,040  -->  00:00:38,895
you need to perform repetitive tasks on a collection of items.

13

00:00:38,895  -->  00:00:41,180
To see for loops in action,

14

00:00:41,180  -->  00:00:44,600
let's start with a basic example of a for loop.

15

00:00:44,600  -->  00:00:48,980
When we have a list of items such as items in a shopping cart,

16

00:00:48,980  -->  00:00:55,260
we might want to run a specific function where there are items in that list.

17

00:00:55,260  -->  00:01:01,000
Let's see an example. First, we'll create a variable called cart,

18

00:01:01,000  -->  00:01:06,880
and we'll set that equal to a list or array of items.

19

00:01:07,420  -->  00:01:09,920
Which I will put in here.

20

00:01:09,920  -->  00:01:12,240
These will be a list of fruits.

21

00:01:12,240  -->  00:01:17,425
Then for each item in cart,

22

00:01:17,425  -->  00:01:19,510
so we'll say for item in cart,

23

00:01:19,510  -->  00:01:25,045
we're going to print each item, like so.

24

00:01:25,045  -->  00:01:29,300
In this example, the for loop iterates over each item in the cart,

25

00:01:29,300  -->  00:01:34,420
which is a list right here and prints each item.

26

00:01:34,420  -->  00:01:38,040
The word item is our loop variable,

27

00:01:38,040  -->  00:01:43,520
a temporary variable placeholder that takes the value of each element in the sequence,

28

00:01:43,520  -->  00:01:47,250
which for us in this example is cart.

29

00:01:47,250  -->  00:01:49,140
In this code snippet,

30

00:01:49,140  -->  00:01:51,940
the first item will be apple,

31

00:01:51,940  -->  00:01:53,740
which is at index 0.

32

00:01:53,740  -->  00:01:57,335
Then the second item will be banana, index 1.

33

00:01:57,335  -->  00:02:00,000
Then the third will be cherry,

34

00:02:00,000  -->  00:02:01,860
index 2, and finally,

35

00:02:01,860  -->  00:02:09,320
the last item in the list is grapefruit at index 3 of this array.

36

00:02:09,320  -->  00:02:13,340
Here's a breakdown of how this for loop works.

37

00:02:13,340  -->  00:02:20,740
The loop variable item takes on the value of each element in the list cart one by one.

38

00:02:20,740  -->  00:02:23,680
For each value of item,

39

00:02:23,680  -->  00:02:26,260
the code block inside the loop executes,

40

00:02:26,260  -->  00:02:28,915
which we have as printing the item.

41

00:02:28,915  -->  00:02:35,660
The structure is for item in list,

42

00:02:35,660  -->  00:02:38,960
and the item part can be anything we want.

43

00:02:38,960  -->  00:02:44,120
We just need to make sure that it follows the format of for something in a group,

44

00:02:44,120  -->  00:02:50,380
and that group needs to correspond to a list array of items to iterate over.

45

00:02:50,380  -->  00:02:54,640
For this example, our list is cart.

46

00:02:55,280  -->  00:03:00,210
Can you guess what the output is going to be when we execute the cell?

47

00:03:00,210  -->  00:03:06,730
Let's find out. The output of this loop will be apple,

48

00:03:06,730  -->  00:03:09,170
banana, cherry, and grape fruit.

49

00:03:09,170  -->  00:03:11,350
If you said this, you're right.

50

00:03:11,350  -->  00:03:14,490
So long as there is an item in the cart,

51

00:03:14,490  -->  00:03:17,230
the for loop will print the item in the cart.

52

00:03:17,230  -->  00:03:19,190
Once there are no more items,

53

00:03:19,190  -->  00:03:20,930
there will be nothing left to print,

54

00:03:20,930  -->  00:03:24,995
and then the for loop would know to stop.

55

00:03:24,995  -->  00:03:28,200
One of the superpowers of the for loop is that it

56

00:03:28,200  -->  00:03:31,780
automatically adjusts to the number of items in the list.

57

00:03:31,780  -->  00:03:36,440
If the list changes should items be added or removed from the group,

58

00:03:36,440  -->  00:03:41,340
the loop will still work correctly without any changes needed for our Python code.

59

00:03:41,340  -->  00:03:45,000
This makes our for loops incredibly powerful and

60

00:03:45,000  -->  00:03:49,485
flexible for handling collections of items when those items are changing.

61

00:03:49,485  -->  00:03:53,620
Let's explore three common scenarios where for loops shine,

62

00:03:53,620  -->  00:03:55,480
such as with numbers.

63

00:03:55,480  -->  00:04:00,280
We often use for loops to iterate over a sequence of numbers.

64

00:04:00,280  -->  00:04:05,680
This is especially useful when you want to perform an action a specific number of times.

65

00:04:05,680  -->  00:04:08,540
In this case, using the range function helps

66

00:04:08,540  -->  00:04:12,460
generate the sequence of numbers for the loop to iterate over.

67

00:04:12,460  -->  00:04:13,980
Next is with strings.

68

00:04:13,980  -->  00:04:17,720
For loops can also iterate over each character in a string.

69

00:04:17,720  -->  00:04:21,140
This allows you to break down a word or sentence into

70

00:04:21,140  -->  00:04:25,105
its individual characters and perform actions on them one by one.

71

00:04:25,105  -->  00:04:28,905
Lastly, let's talk about using loops with collections.

72

00:04:28,905  -->  00:04:31,660
For loops can iterate over various collections,

73

00:04:31,660  -->  00:04:34,080
such as lists, tuples, and sets.

74

00:04:34,080  -->  00:04:37,900
This is incredibly useful for processing each item in a collection,

75

00:04:37,900  -->  00:04:40,755
like printing each fruit in a shopping cart list.

76

00:04:40,755  -->  00:04:43,960
One important point to note here is,

77

00:04:43,960  -->  00:04:48,980
remember to use for loops when you know the number of items or iterations ahead of time.

78

00:04:48,980  -->  00:04:50,820
They are your go to tool for

79

00:04:50,820  -->  00:04:54,760
repetitive tasks when the sequence or collection is well defined,

80

00:04:54,760  -->  00:04:59,040
like items in a shopping cart or a specific set of numbers.
